+      <h3>Sequence strip and Pattern Delay</h3>
+      <ul class="help-compact">
+        <li>The strip shows the active pattern name or <strong>AUTO SOLVE</strong> plus every move token.</li>
+        <li>The current token is accented and enlarged, completed tokens stay tinted, and upcoming tokens remain muted.</li>
+        <li>The strip persists after playback and is replaced by the next pattern or solution. Scramble and Reset hide it.</li>
+        <li>When controls are hidden, the strip drops toward the bottom edge so it remains visible.</li>
+        <li>The <strong>Delay</strong> slider ranges from 0.25 to 5 seconds in 0.25-second steps. It inserts a pause after each non-final pattern move only. It does not slow manual turns, Scramble, guide algorithms, or AUTO SOLVE.</li>
+        <li>Delay is read live, so changing it during a pattern changes the remaining pauses.</li>
+      </ul>
+
+      <h3>Cube Color Palette</h3>
+      <p>The Color Palette dropdown recolors the six shared sticker slots without moving or resetting any cubie. The slot order is white/U, yellow/D, blue/B, green/F, red/R, and orange/L. Palettes can be changed while solved, scrambled, patterned, moving, or automatically solving.</p>
+      <p>The standard scheme plus 20 alternate named palettes are included. Reset retains the selected palette; reloading the page returns to Standard Rubik’s because CUBED does not store settings.</p>
+      <details class="help-details">
+        <summary>Show all alternate palette names</summary>
+        <p>Neon Arcade · Retro 1970s · Desert Sunset · Ocean Reef · Pastel Candy · Gothic Jewel · Earth &amp; Clay · Bauhaus · Nordic Winter · Japanese Garden · Miami Vice · Forest Mushroom · Ice Cream Shop · Cyberpunk · Autumn Leaves · Southwestern Tile · Galaxy · Color-Vision Friendly · ColorBrewer Set2 · Mineral Spectrum.</p>
+      </details>
+
+      <h3>Eight-step beginner solving guide</h3>
+      <p><strong>GUIDE</strong> opens the lesson panel. The header shows <strong>STEP n / 8</strong> and eight progress ticks. Back and Next navigate the lessons; the step-eight button reads <strong>Start over</strong> and returns to step one. Every algorithm block has a <strong>▶ Play</strong> button that queues the displayed moves on the cube from its current state. Guide Play is temporarily ignored during AUTO SOLVE.</p>
+      <p>The guide teaches: meeting the cube and notation, the white cross, white corners, middle-layer edges, the yellow cross, lining up yellow edges, placing yellow corners, and twisting the final corners. Closing and reopening GUIDE preserves the current lesson while the page remains open.</p>
 
-      <h3>Themes</h3>
-      <p>The top theme pills switch among <strong>Nebula</strong>, <strong>Synthwave</strong>, <strong>Daylight</strong>, and <strong>Ember</strong>. Each theme changes the page background, interface accent, glass panels, scene lighting, rim color, stars, ground shadow, and—where appropriate—the Synthwave grid. Daylight also changes the interface to light glass with dark text. Scene changes blend smoothly rather than switching abruptly.</p>
+      <h3>Visual themes</h3>
+      <p>The top pills select <strong>Nebula</strong>, <strong>Synthwave</strong>, <strong>Daylight</strong>, or <strong>Ember</strong>. Each changes the background, interface accent, glass panels, scene lighting, rim light, star visibility, ground shadow, and—on Synthwave—the perspective grid. Daylight switches to light glass and dark text. Scene lighting blends smoothly instead of jumping.</p>
 
       <h3>Rail buttons and clean-view mode</h3>
-      <p><strong>GUIDE</strong> shows or hides the tutorial panel. <strong>CONTROLS</strong> shows or hides the entire move deck; when the deck is hidden, a visible pattern sequence drops toward the bottom edge. Hide both GUIDE and CONTROLS for an uncluttered full-screen cube. Lit rail buttons indicate which panel or overlay is active.</p>
